<p>
    One of the most important — and most misunderstood — factors in Wi‑Fi
    performance is the frequency band a standard operates on. Every major shift
    in Wi‑Fi history involves a deliberate tradeoff between three bands.
</p>
<div class="freq-panels">
    <div class="freq-panel freq-panel--24" data-ghz="2.4">
        <h4>2.4 GHz</h4>
        <p>The oldest and most widely‑used band…</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Best range and wall penetration</li>
            <li>Only 3 non‑overlapping channels</li>
            <li>High interference in dense environments</li>
            <li>Used in: Wi‑Fi 1, 3, 4, 6</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="freq-panel freq-panel--5" data-ghz="5">
        <h4>5 GHz</h4>
        <p>Trades range and penetration…</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Moderate range, struggles with walls</li>
            <li>Up to 23 non‑overlapping channels</li>
            <li>Low interference, higher throughput</li>
            <li>Used in: Wi‑Fi 2, 4, 5, 6</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="freq-panel freq-panel--6" data-ghz="6">
        <h4>6 GHz</h4>
        <p>Introduced with Wi‑Fi 6E…</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Shortest range, worst wall penetration</li>
            <li>Up to 59 non‑overlapping channels</li>
            <li>Virtually zero legacy interference</li>
            <li>Used in: Wi‑Fi 6E, 7</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</div>
<p>
    Understanding these tradeoffs is key to understanding why each Wi‑Fi
    generation made the design choices it did.
</p>